name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor DeMowbray was born on 25 March 1364, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Sir John de Mowbray III. She married Sir Lewis Clifford on 12 February 1373, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1399, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 35."},"et":{"25 MAR 1364–1399":"25. märts 1364–1399","1364–1399":"1364–1399","1352–1421":"1352–1421","1359–1404":"1359–1404","1387–1421":"1387–1421","1390–1438":"1390–1438","1340–1368":"1340–1368","12 FEB 1372/73":"12. veebruar 1373","1352":"1352","1340":"1340","17 June 1368":"17. juuni 1368","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","1359":"1359","MAY 1386":"mai 1386","1368":"1368","1399":"1399","1421":"1421","1387":"1387","1364":"1364","25 MAR 1364":"